net.akami.mask.merge

Interface MergeBehavior<T>

  • Type Parameters:
    T -
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    ElementAdditionMerge, EncapsulatorMerge, FractionAdditionMerge, MonomialAdditionMerge, PairNullifying, VariableCombination

    public interface MergeBehavior<T>
    WARNING : The javadoc of this interface is not up to date thus is not valid. It will be rewritten soon. Describes an element which, once in a list, can be merged with another element from another list or from the list itself, under certain conditions. Basically, you have two lists, both containing the same kind of elements. Theses elements must implement the MergeBehavior interface. You can then merge these two lists into one single list. if two elements from different lists are mergeables (defined by the #isMergeable(T, T) method), a result defined by the #mergeElement(T, T) method will be added into a new list. In the end, all elements which could not be merged will be added into the new list. Example : Our object SuperNumber implements the MergeBehavior interface. isMergeable() returns true if the float handled by the SuperNumber class equals the float of the compared SuperNumber.

    • Method Detail

      • isMergeable

        boolean isMergeable(T a,
                    T b)
        Defines whether an element can be effectively merged with another. If yes, then #mergeElement(MergeBehavior) will be called, computing a new result from the two elements. 
        
 Note that the interface automatically refuses any merge including two elements from different types.
 Thus no instance check or cast is required inside the method.
        

        

        Parameters:
        

        other - the other element to compare with the object itself
        

        Returns:
        

        whether the two elements are mergeable
